Professor Raymond Parson of the University of the North West School of Business says government should urgently come up with a recovery programme after South Africa slipped into a technical recession. The economy contracted by 0.7% in the second quarter, after a 2%  contraction in the first quarter. The largest contribution to the decline came from the agricultural sector. Parsons says the current situation requires government to be pro-active. “We need to establish a policy environment of both certainty and more consistency, whether it’s land reform or the mining charter or the visas in tourism. All these issues add up to a negative environment that needs to be turned around sooner rather than later. The red lights are there. Moody’s have already said the latest growth figures and their implications are what they call credit negative.” Watch for more:   